<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1920-05-19T14:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1920-05-19T14:00:00-05:00" n="870" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d870">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">631.6131/187: Telegram</note>
                            <head><hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Great Britain</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Davis</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                    State</gloss></hi></head>
                            <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">London</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1920-05-19T20:00:00+01:00"><hi rend="italic">May 19,
                                            1920—8 p.m.</hi></date><lb/>[Received May 19—5:42
                                    p.m.]</dateline></opener>
                            <p>824. My 791, May 14, 6 p.m.<note n="99" xml:id="d870fn99">Not
                                    printed.</note> I have received an intimation in an entirely
                                unofficial manner that in order to keep our Government informed of
                                developments an invitation may be extended for an American
                                representative to be present at all meetings of the Permanent
                                Committee of the Supreme Economic Council at which the question of
                                Russian trade is discussed. I should welcome an early expression of
                                the Department’s desires should such invitation be received.</p>
                            <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Davis</hi></signed></closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>